# Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) Report on the Titanic Dataset

## 1. Introduction

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) is an important step in the data analysis process that helps understand the structure, quality, and characteristics of a dataset. It involves summarizing the data using descriptive statistics and visualizations to identify patterns, relationships, trends, and anomalies before applying machine learning models.

The objective of this project is to perform Exploratory Data Analysis on the Titanic dataset using Python libraries such as Pandas, Matplotlib, and Seaborn.

---

# 2. Objective

* To understand the structure of the Titanic dataset.
* To identify missing values and data quality issues.
* To analyze numerical and categorical variables.
* To discover relationships between variables.
* To summarize key insights obtained from the dataset.

---

# 3. Tools and Technologies Used

* Python
* Pandas
* NumPy
* Matplotlib
* Seaborn
* Jupyter Notebook

---

# 4. Dataset Description

The Titanic dataset contains passenger information from the Titanic ship disaster. Each record represents one passenger and includes demographic details, ticket information, passenger class, fare, cabin information, and survival status.

Important features include:

* PassengerId
* Survived
* Pclass
* Name
* Sex
* Age
* SibSp
* Parch
* Ticket
* Fare
* Cabin
* Embarked

---

# 5. Data Exploration

The dataset was explored using the following Pandas functions:

* head()
* info()
* describe()
* value_counts()
* isnull().sum()
* duplicated().sum()

These functions helped understand the dataset structure, data types, summary statistics, missing values, and duplicate records.

---

# 6. Data Preprocessing

During the exploration process, missing values were identified in the following columns:

* Age
* Cabin
* Embarked

The following preprocessing steps were performed:

* Missing values in the Age column were replaced using the median age.
* Missing values in the Embarked column were filled using the most frequent value (mode).
* The Cabin column was removed because it contained a large number of missing values.
* Duplicate records were checked before analysis.

These preprocessing steps improved the quality of the dataset for further analysis.

---

# 7. Exploratory Data Analysis

## 7.1 Age Distribution

A histogram was created to analyze passenger age distribution.

Observation:

* Most passengers were between 20 and 40 years of age.
* Very few passengers were above 60 years.
* The age distribution was slightly right-skewed.

---

## 7.2 Fare Distribution

A histogram was plotted to analyze ticket fare distribution.

Observation:

* Most passengers paid relatively low fares.
* A small number of passengers paid very high fares.
* The fare distribution contained several outliers.

---

## 7.3 Boxplot of Age

A boxplot was used to identify age outliers.

Observation:

* A few age values appeared as outliers.
* Most passenger ages were concentrated around the median.

---

## 7.4 Boxplot of Fare

Observation:

* Several high-value fare outliers were detected.
* Most ticket fares were within a lower price range.

---

## 7.5 Survival Count

A count plot was used to visualize passenger survival.

Observation:

* More passengers died than survived.
* Survival rate was lower than the non-survival rate.

---

## 7.6 Gender Distribution

Observation:

* Male passengers were more numerous than female passengers.

---

## 7.7 Passenger Class Distribution

Observation:

* Most passengers traveled in Third Class.
* First Class contained the fewest passengers.

---

## 7.8 Survival by Gender

Observation:

* Female passengers had a significantly higher survival rate.
* Most male passengers did not survive.

---

## 7.9 Survival by Passenger Class

Observation:

* First Class passengers had the highest survival rate.
* Third Class passengers experienced the highest number of deaths.

---

## 7.10 Scatter Plot (Age vs Fare)

Observation:

* Most passengers paid low fares regardless of age.
* No strong linear relationship was observed between age and fare.
* High-fare outliers were visible.

---

## 7.11 Correlation Heatmap

Observation:

* Fare showed a positive correlation with survival.
* Passenger class had a negative correlation with fare and survival.
* No severe multicollinearity was observed among the numerical variables.

---

## 7.12 Pairplot

Observation:

* Pairplot showed relationships among numerical variables.
* Higher fare values were generally associated with a higher survival probability.
* Passenger class and fare exhibited a noticeable relationship.

---

# 8. Key Findings

* The dataset contains passenger information from the Titanic disaster.
* Missing values were successfully handled during preprocessing.
* Most passengers were between 20 and 40 years old.
* The majority of passengers traveled in Third Class.
* Male passengers were more numerous than female passengers.
* Female passengers had a much higher survival rate.
* First Class passengers had better chances of survival.
* Most passengers paid low ticket fares, while a few paid exceptionally high fares.
* Fare showed a positive relationship with survival.
* Correlation analysis revealed no strong multicollinearity among the numerical variables.

---

# 9. Conclusion

Exploratory Data Analysis provided valuable insights into the Titanic dataset by identifying important trends, relationships, and data quality issues. The analysis showed that passenger class, gender, and fare significantly influenced survival outcomes. Data preprocessing improved dataset quality by handling missing values appropriately. Overall, EDA proved to be an essential step for understanding the dataset and preparing it for future predictive modeling and machine learning applications.

---

# 10. Outcome

This project successfully demonstrated the application of Exploratory Data Analysis techniques using Python. Statistical summaries and visualizations helped identify patterns, trends, and anomalies in the Titanic dataset, providing a strong foundation for future data science and machine learning tasks.
